[ProMED thanks Mahmoud Orabi for this submission.

Bashkiria, also called the Republic of Bashkortostan, is a republic of Russia located between the Volga (the longest river in Europe) and the Ural Mountains, with a population of 4 million; its capital and largest city is Ufa (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bashkortostan). Bashkiria is one of 14 federal subjects in the Volga Federal District, which forms the southeastern part of European Russia. A map of the Volga Federal District showing the location of Bashkiria (indicated as 1 on the map) within the Volga Federal District can be found at https://bit.ly/3G5XT6x. Saratov, the region in the Volga Federal District that is most affected by syphilis according to the news report above, is indicated as 10 on this map. A map of Russia showing the location of Bashkiria can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/place/Republic+of+Bashkortostan,+Russia.

Syphilis is a sexually transmitted infection, caused by the spirochetal bacterium _Treponema pallidum_. Person-to-person transmission of syphilis can occur during vaginal, anal, or oral sex by direct contact with the sore that characterizes the primary stage of syphilis, known as a chancre. Chancres can occur on or around the external genitals, in the vagina, around the anus, or in the rectum, or in or around the mouth. Syphilis can also be transmitted by direct contact with the skin rashes or mucous membrane lesions (in the mouth, vagina, or anus) that characterize secondary syphilis. Pregnant women with syphilis can transmit the infection to their unborn child.

Although syphilis transmission has occurred via blood transfusion in the past, transmission by this route is believed to be very rare since the implementation of screening of the blood supply and refrigeration of blood products (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5973824/). Transmission has also occurred in recipients following organ transplantation (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5973824/).

Sharing contaminated items such as sex toys could also transmit the disease (https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/syphilis/). Using a razor after it has been in contact with infected sores may also transmit the disease (https://yoursexualhealth.co.uk/blog/ca-you-catch-syphilis-without-having-sex/), as has occupational exposure to syphilis via accidental injury with a surgical scalpel (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5973824/). However, transmission is unlikely via toilet seats, cutlery, and towels (https://yoursexualhealth.co.uk/blog/ca-you-catch-syphilis-without-having-sex/). - Mod.ML

